<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">39137516</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2024</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>02</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2024</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>23</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1532-1983</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>43</Volume><Issue>9</Issue><PubDate><Year>2024</Year><Month>Sep</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Clinical nutrition (Edinburgh, Scotland)</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Clin Nutr</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Assessment of exercise-induced dehydration in underhydrated athletes: Which method shows the most promise?</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>2139</StartPage><EndPage>2148</EndPage><MedlinePgn>2139-2148</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.clnu.2024.08.003</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0261-5614(24)00281-4</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND &amp; AIMS" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">Athletes are commonly exposed to exercise-induced dehydration. However, the best method to detect dehydration under this circumstance is not clear. This study aimed to analyze pre- and post-dehydration measurements of biomarkers, including saliva osmolality (SOsm), urine osmolality (UOsm), urine-specific gravity (USG), urine color (Ucolor), serum osmolality (SeOsm), serum arginine vasopressin (AVP), serum sodium (Na<sup>+</sup>), and thirst sensation in underhydrated athletes, using the body mass loss (BML) as the reference method.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">In this clinical trial (NCT05380089), a total of 38 athletes (17 females) with a regular low water intake (&lt;35&#xa0;mL/kg/day) were submitted to exercise-induced dehydration with a heat index of 29.8&#xa0;&#xb1;&#xa0;3.1&#xa0;&#xb0;C and an individualized running intensity (80-90% of first ventilatory threshold).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">ROC curve analysis revealed significant discriminative abilities of SOsm, with AUC values of 0.76&#xa0;at 1.5% BML, 0.75&#xa0;at 1.75% BML, and 0.87&#xa0;at 2% BML, while Na<sup>+</sup> and SeOsm showed the highest AUC of 0.87 and 0.91&#xa0;at 2% BML, respectively. SOsm showed high sensitivity at 1.5% of BML, while SeOsm and Na<sup>+</sup> demonstrated high sensitivity at 2% of BML.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">This study highlights SOsm as a potential indicator of hydration status across different levels of BML. Additionally, Na<sup>+</sup> and SeOsm emerged as accurate dehydration predictors at 1.75% and 2% of BML. Notably, the accuracy of urinary indices and thirst sensation for detecting hydration may be limited.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2024 The Authors. Published by Elsevier Ltd.. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Francisco</LastName><ForeName>R&#xfa;ben</ForeName><Initials>R</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Exercise and Health Laboratory, CIPER, Faculdade Motricidade Humana, Universidade de Lisboa, Lisbon, Portugal. Electronic address: rubenfrancisco@fmh.ulisboa.pt.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Jesus</LastName><ForeName>Filipe</ForeName><Initials>F</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Exercise and Health Laboratory, CIPER, Faculdade Motricidade Humana, Universidade de Lisboa, Lisbon, Portugal.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Di Vincenzo</LastName><ForeName>Olivia</ForeName><Initials>O</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Public Health, Federico II University of Naples, Italy.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Nunes</LastName><ForeName>Catarina L</ForeName><Initials>CL</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affil